@Tutorial(time: 25) {
    @Intro(title: "Read the Tree Without Allocating") {
        A Cambium tree is meant to be queried frequently â€” by IDEs on
        every keystroke, by analyzers walking every node, by formatters
        emitting bytes. To stay within reasonable memory and ARC
        budgets the primary traversal API is borrowed: walks happen
        through `~Copyable` cursors handed to a closure, and source
        text is exposed as a chunk-streaming view rather than a
        materialized `String`.

        In this tutorial you implement nine REPL commands â€” `:tree`,
        `:at`, `:cover`, `:contains`, `:find`, `:slice`, `:hash`,
        `:nodes`, `:tokens` â€” each one a different shape of borrowed
        or owned tree access.
    }

    @Section(title: "Walk with borrowed cursors") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            ``CambiumCore/SyntaxTree/withRoot(_:)`` and
            ``CambiumCore/SharedSyntaxTree/withRoot(_:)`` both hand a
            borrowed ``CambiumCore/SyntaxNodeCursor`` to your closure.
            Inside the closure you can iterate children with
            ``CambiumCore/SyntaxNodeCursor/forEachChild(_:)``,
            ``CambiumCore/SyntaxNodeCursor/forEachChildOrToken(_:)``
            (interleaving tokens with nodes), or descend recursively
            with ``CambiumCore/SyntaxNodeCursor/visitPreorder(_:)``.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Create `CalculatorDebugDump.swift` with a stub
                `calculatorDebugTree(_:)` that returns an empty
                string. The next step fills it in.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorDebugDump.swift", file: "04-debug-01-empty.swift")
            }

            @Step {
                Implement the dump as a recursive walk over borrowed
                cursors. The `withRoot` closure receives a borrowed
                cursor on the root; `forEachChildOrToken` interleaves
                node and token children in source order so trivia ends
                up between significant siblings.

                Because the cursor is borrowed (via a `borrowing`
                parameter), the recursive call costs zero ARC traffic.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorDebugDump.swift", file: "04-debug-02-borrowed-walk.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Position-based queries") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            Cambium ships two positional queries built on the cursor
            API: ``CambiumCore/SyntaxNodeCursor/withTokenAtOffset(_:none:single:between:)``
            for "what token owns this byte?" and
            ``CambiumCore/SyntaxNodeCursor/withCoveringElement(_:_:)``
            for "what's the smallest element covering this range?"
            Both shapes are core to building IDE features like cursor
            inspection and syntax-aware selection.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Add `describeToken(at:)` and `describeCovering(_:)`
                methods on `CalculatorParseResult`. The token query
                forces the caller to address all three cases â€”
                off-the-end, inside-a-token, and at-a-boundary â€” by
                accepting a closure per case.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorParseResult.swift", file: "04-result-01-position-queries.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Stream source text as bytes") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            ``CambiumCore/SyntaxNodeCursor/withText(_:)`` exposes the
            subtree's bytes through a ``CambiumCore/SyntaxText`` view
            that walks the green tree on demand and yields chunks
            straight from the resolver's interned bytes â€” no copies,
            no `String` allocation. `SyntaxText` offers `contains`,
            `firstRange(of:)`, and `sliced(_:)` over the chunk view, so
            most byte-level scans stay allocation-free for the
            document.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Add `sourceContains`, `sourceFirstRange(of:)`, and
                `sourceSlice(_:)`. Only the *needle* is materialized
                as an `Array` â€” the document is streamed.

                For `sourceSlice` the range is bounds-checked against
                `text.utf8Count` since `SyntaxText.sliced(_:)` traps
                on out-of-bounds ranges.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorParseResult.swift", file: "04-result-02-syntaxtext.swift")
            }

            @Step {
                Define a custom ``CambiumCore/UTF8Sink`` and feed the
                source bytes into it via
                ``CambiumCore/SyntaxText/writeUTF8(to:)``. Here the sink
                is an FNV-1a hasher; the same shape works for
                checksums, byte counters, or any other reduction over
                the document.

                The sink's `write(_:)` is called once per chunk in the
                green tree. Two parses of identical source feed the
                same byte sequence into the hasher and produce
                identical hashes.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorParseResult.swift", file: "04-result-03-utf8sink.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Section(title: "Owned handles for stored references") {
        @ContentAndMedia {
            Borrowed cursors cannot escape their closure â€” that is
            what makes them allocation-free. When you need to store a
            node reference, send it across actors, or iterate in an
            order the cursor API does not directly support, promote
            it to an owned ``CambiumCore/SyntaxNodeHandle`` (or
            ``CambiumCore/SyntaxTokenHandle``).

            Handles are copyable, `Sendable`, `Hashable`, and carry an
            ARC retain on the underlying tree storage. Allocate them
            for end-of-pipeline storage; do not allocate them per-node
            during a hot walk.

            ``CambiumOwnedTraversal`` provides the convenience
            allocators the REPL uses for `:nodes` and `:tokens`.
        }

        @Steps {
            @Step {
                Add `expressionHandles` and `tokenHandles(in:)` on
                `CalculatorParseResult`. The first uses
                ``CambiumOwnedTraversal`` to materialize every
                descendant handle in preorder, then filters to
                expression-shape kinds. The second uses
                `SyntaxNodeHandle.tokenHandles(in:)` (also from
                ``CambiumOwnedTraversal``) to materialize a range of
                token handles.

                @Code(name: "CalculatorParseResult.swift", file: "04-result-04-owned-handles.swift")
            }
        }
    }

    @Assessments {
        @MultipleChoice {
            What does ``CambiumCore/SyntaxText`` allow you to do that
            ``CambiumCore/SyntaxNodeCursor/makeString()`` does not?

            @Choice(isCorrect: false) {
                Mutate the source bytes in place.

                @Justification(reaction: "Try again") {
                    `SyntaxText` is read-only. Editing happens via
                    `SharedSyntaxTree.replacing(_:with:context:)` â€”
                    covered in Chapter 3.
                }
            }

            @Choice(isCorrect: true) {
                Read the document chunk-by-chunk through a
                ``CambiumCore/UTF8Sink`` without materializing a
                `String` for the whole source.

                @Justification(reaction: "That's right") {
                    `SyntaxText` is the streaming view; `makeString()`
                    is the materializing convenience. For hashing,
                    scanning, and large-document reads, prefer
                    `withText`.
                }
            }

            @Choice(isCorrect: false) {
                Modify the tree's structure.

                @Justification(reaction: "Try again") {
                    `SyntaxText` exposes only the read view; tree
                    structure is not addressable through it.
                }
            }
        }

        @MultipleChoice {
            When should you reach for an owned
            ``CambiumCore/SyntaxNodeHandle`` instead of staying inside
            a borrowed-cursor closure?

            @Choice(isCorrect: false) {
                Whenever the tree exceeds 1000 nodes.

                @Justification(reaction: "Try again") {
                    Tree size is not the deciding factor. Borrowed
                    cursors stay efficient regardless of node count.
                }
            }

            @Choice(isCorrect: true) {
                When you need to store the reference, send it across
                actors, or pass it to APIs that take owned handles
                (typed AST overlays, analysis caches).

                @Justification(reaction: "That's right") {
                    Handles cost an ARC retain and an `Array`
                    allocation per call to the owned-traversal
                    helpers; the trade is worth it once the reference
                    needs to outlive the borrow scope.
                }
            }

            @Choice(isCorrect: false) {
                For every leaf token, to keep the cursor stack short.

                @Justification(reaction: "Try again") {
                    Borrowed cursors do not stack-allocate per node;
                    making handles for every token would just churn
                    the heap.
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
